The paper discusses dynamic programming algorithms on tree decompositions, which are commonly used in the field of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The focus is on the Steiner Tree problem, which is a classic problem in discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The paper also involves computational geometry, as the Steiner Tree problem is often studied in the context of geometric graphs (cs.CG). The use of representative sets and Gaussian elimination suggests an artificial intelligence (cs.AI) approach, and the optimization of dynamic programming algorithms is a topic in computational complexity (cs.CC).
